statement:
Show that \begin{enumerate} \item $a! + b! + 2026$ is not a perfect square for any positive integers $a$ and $b$.
\item for every positive integer $n$, there exists a positive integer $k$ such that \[ a_1! + a_2! + \dots + a_n! + k \]is not a perfect square for any positive integers $a_1$, $a_2$, $\dots$, $a_n$.
\end{enumerate}

Let $p \ne q$ be coprime positive integers. Determine all infinite sequences $a_1$, $a_2$, $\dots$ of positive integers such that the following conditions hold for all $n \ge 1$:
\begin{align*}
    \max(a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{n+p}) - \min(a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{n+p}) &= p \\
    \max(a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{n+q}) - \min(a_n, a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{n+q}) &= q   
\end{align*}

Let $\mathbb{Z}^+$ be the set of positive integers. Determine, with proof, whether there exist functions $f, g: \mathbb{Z}^+ \to \mathbb{Z}^+$ such that
\begin{align*}
f(g(g(x))) &= 3x \\
g(f(g(x))) &= 5x \\ g(g(f(x))) &= 7x 
\end{align*}
for all $x \in \mathbb{Z}^+$.

Let $\mathbb{N}$ be the set of positive integers. Find all functions $f\colon \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{N}$ that simultaneously satisfy the following properties:
\begin{enumerate}[(i)]
\item $f(mn) = f(m)f(n)$ for all positive integers $m$ and $n$;

\item There exists a positive integer $c$ such that $f(n) \le n^c$ for all positive integers $n$;

\item The numbers $f(n) + m$ and $f(m) + n + 1$ are coprime for all positive integers $m$ and $n$.
\end{enumerate}

Hint 2:
Consider a bipartite graph with $X$ and $Y$. Show that you can draw $2n - 1$ directed edges S.T.

\begin{itemize}
    \item There is an edge towards each vertex other than $x$.
    \item No two segments intersect in their interior.
    \item For any edge $e = \overrightarrow{e_1 e_2}$, $e_1 \geq e_2$.
\end{itemize}

