\begin{title} \textbf{Solution (EpicGrowth)} \end{title}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Consider the given sequence over $\mathbb{F}_n$, and let $a_n = P^n(0)$, where $P^n (a) = P(P(\cdots (a)))$.
\newline
\\ Next, we have that as the sequence is not constant, there are some minimal pairs of $P^i(0), P^j (0)$ such that $a_i = a_j$, where $i < j$.
\newline
\\  By minimality, we get that we can reduce to the modulo of $n$, and hence choosing $a = P^{i-1}(0), b = P^{j-1}(0)$, we get that $P(a) \equiv P(b) \pmod{n}$ and $0 \le a < b \le n-1 $.
